Explanations for global competitiveness.
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report (Competitiveness Report) for the year 2001.
In the 75-country study, Finland, the United States, and Canada occupy places one to three, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe take the last places.
(All the rankings can be accessed at www.weforum.com.)
As a co-leader of this annual study, I am often asked what competitiveness actually means.
Is there a competitive economic rivalry among countries in addition to the military one?
Does it make sense at all to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is precisely defined as the ability of a country to achieve sustainable economic growth over the medium term – namely, within a period of five years.
This definition does not imply, however, that the competitiveness of one country says anything about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries on earth could simultaneously achieve higher growth.
It is nonetheless sensible to establish a ranking list of countries with regard to their growth capabilities.
Each country is interested in knowing whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep pace with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In many respects, economic growth can be likened to a sporting competition, where the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another.
Countries compete, for example, for international mobile capital.
The more a country can secure foreign direct investments for itself, the less another country gets.
Each country is interested in knowing whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep pace with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
When Intel plans to build a new semiconductor plant, various countries are invited to submit bids.
The competition for the contract is fierce and many countries also attract investors with tax incentives, improved infrastructure, and even customized study plans at the local technical university.
This year, we measured a country's competitiveness (growth capacity) based on three broad criteria: (1) technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we calculated indicators, whose average values were calculated using a specific method to then establish a general growth and competitiveness index.
This criterion refers to a country's ability to drive new developments and apply technologies that have been developed elsewhere.
Some countries such as the US, Japan, South Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development, thereby achieving high values in the area of innovation.
Other countries such as Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and thus achieve little in terms of new products and procedures.
Countries with a high degree of innovation tend to enjoy a high standard of living as a result of these innovations.
In this area, the US, Canada, and Finland take the top three places on the ranking list.
This criterion refers to the quality of governance.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts impartial and corruption-free?
Can one trust that the government will fulfill its commitments properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and ineffective judges.
High ethical standards promote economic productivity.
In this respect, the Nordic countries are globally leading and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also the top performers on the ranking list.
Corruption is almost unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced national budget, a realistic exchange rate of the national currency, the ability of businesses and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high confidence that the government will meet its financial obligations.
By studying the example of Asia in the late 1990s, we have learned that a macroeconomic crisis can undermine economic growth even if companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the global economy can be divided into two categories of countries: the innovation-driven and the non-innovation-driven.
Only about 20 countries actively engage in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which are among the wealthiest in the world, a superior system of technological innovations is considered a prerequisite for sustained competitiveness.
Universities must be excellent, state laboratories should have world-class standards, and the government and industry should strongly invest in research and development.
A key indicator for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend higher schools and universities after completing their compulsory education.
In the US and Canada, this proportion is 80 %.
For the "non-innovation-driven" countries, technology is equally important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed domestically.
Some countries excel at importing new technologies, while others do not.
Over the past ten or fifteen years, the majority of technology imports occurred as part of foreign direct investments.
American companies that heavily invested in Mexico, or Taiwanese companies that invested in mainland China, also brought in new technologies that increased the efficiency of production in the respective target country's economy.
Therefore, it was indeed reasonable for the relevant countries to make every effort to secure these foreign investments: they bring not only capital, but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our rankings are not suited to evaluating short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do provide insight into the long-term prospects of major economies.
It is therefore an irony that many of the countries that top this year's rankings, such as the US or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while others, further down the list, such as China (ranked 39), are not affected by the global recession.
Partially, the slowdown in the economy is related to the terrorist attacks of September 11, but it is increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected to it through trade and production networks were already slipping into recession before September.
We are of the opinion that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the US will regain its ability to achieve strong economic growth over the next five years.
